@node "INTRODUCTION"
@title "Grunch · Introduction"


    @{b}Introduction@{ub}

	Grunch is a multi OS application keeping downloading, installing, updating
	and uninstalling away from the user.

	Sounds like a packet manager? Maybe, but Grunch is more. It's a kind of
	software centre, where you can click and search for all the software you
	want. No more searching for the right OS version and the right download
	page, no more dealing with libraries and other files. Grunch is taking over.

	There were other packet managers before and they all failed badly you may
	say. Yes, that is true. They had several design flaws in flexibility.

	1. Servers

	Servers are a good thing, but can be a pain in the ass if they are no longer
	available or persons maintaining the servers are not available when you need
	them.

	2. Support by the developers

	Developers needed to support a packet manager or a software was not be able
	to be used with the manager.

	3. Repacking

	It was always needed to repack the software to make it compatible to the
	packet manager, which made it complicated.

	Those three points killed those previous packet manager projects from
	scratch.

	So what is the solution? Well, Servers are good, but should be easy to
	replace. Support by the developers is good, but if the developer does not
	care about a packet manager it should be fine, too. And no repacking!

	Stupid? Only on the first look. I inverted the first points from bad to
	good. Let's start with the second one. Its not bad to have developers on our
	side, as long as they like to. It´s a help. Speaking about help. There are
	hundreds of people out there able to maintain their system by hand. Why not
	allow them to participate to help, too?

	This is the big goal of Grunch. Everyone can help. Back to the servers.
	Servers in this case are simple http servers. Nothing special, but
	centralised enough to feed the masses out there with new data files.

	Some people are translators and love to fix and update catalogs, while
	others love to use them. Why not bring them together? A simple database file
	on a server and zwoosh. Quick interaction between both groups without any
	need of placing the files into a global overcomplicated database.

	Maintaining of the database is an issue. In other words: What happens when
	geit sits dead in his chair? The solution would be quite easy. Someone would
	take the latest database, change the URL inside to his webpage and uploads
	the database file right to that place. The users now are able to download
	this modified database file once by using a browser and after placing it
	into their Grunch drawer, they get database update from the new source,
	maintained by the new guy. Simple isn't it?

	Well, I talked about updating a lot and you may say "yeah its a packet
	manager".

	It's more!

	Grunch is more than that. People talked about setting up an AppStore for
	MorphOS or AmigaOS. Well, there was much laughter, but frankly it's nice to
	have a central point, where you can search for software and a click later it
	is installed. (iPad user speaking). The result is a more flexible way than
	for example Papiosaur's Pack Ultimate. The pack is nice and helpful for new
	people, but it contains so much nice software which cannot be seen by people
	who already have a preconfigured system, as it's an all or nothing solution.

	And yes I did not install the pack for the same reson, too, but I downloaded
	it to simply drag over the stuff I needed. Grunch is (will be) kind of a
	software store where you search for stuff and install it and if you don't
	like or want it, you uninstall it. Today I got noticed about the OWB update
	by Grunch and a single click later it was installed. Even that click can be
	avoided by disabling update requests and enabling automatically update.

	Dependencies are a big problem not only on MorphOS. Grunch knows and
	supports dependencies for installation and uninstallation. So if you want to
	install a game which needs PowerSDL, Grunch will check if PowerSDL is
	installed and if not a requester will pop up and shows the dependencies of
	the application. If the user continues PowerSDL gets installed, too. If he
	cancels the software installation gets aborted. If the user decides to
	uninstall PowerSDL, he gets a list of all Applications related to the
	PowerSDL and if the user continues all those programs get removed, too.

	One more thing: (yeah stolen)

	I only have a few testers right now, as it is required to have some
	experienced people to find the flaws and bugs as well as providing ideas and
	features request I forgot. So far they seem to be happy with the result. The
	number of applications in list is that small, because I asked them to not
	send any in until the database format is settled. :) But hey! More than 100
	entries is more than all prior packet manager solutions had combined.

@endnode
@node "REQUIREMENTS"
@title "Grunch · Requirements"


    @{b}Requirements@{ub}

	o MorphOS 2.7 is strongly advised. MorphOS 1.x versions are not supported.

	o AmigaOS3 and AmigaOS4 is also supported but mainly untested.

@endnode
@node "FEATURES"
@title "Grunch · Features"


    @{b}Features@{ub}

	o Automatic downloading, installation, repairing and deinstallation of Applications.

	o Automatic update installation (can be configured to manual)

	o MagicBeacon support.

	o Single time update check. Automatically quits after update
	  check was performed, opens user interface if updates where found.

	o Tons of small functions to make your live easier.

	o Full featured Magic User Interface (MUI)

	o Localised

@endnode
@node "INSTALLATION"
@title "Grunch · Installation"


    @{b}Installation@{ub}

	Just drop the Grunch drawer into "SYS:Applications" or any drawer you want
	it to be installed.
			
	On non MorphOS systems it is required to replace the main binary. Get the
	binary specified for your system from the "Grunch/bin/" drawer and drop it
	over the default MorphOS binary to replace it.

	You MUST NOT move or copy any other data delivered with Grunch. If you copy
	or rename these files or try to launch the Grunch binary from inside the
	"bin/"-drawer, Grunch will report your installation to be broken, as it is
	unable to bind the data files into your system at runtime.
			
	Installation done!

	Of course there is an installer script allowing to perform the installation
	and will also create a proper WBStartup icon, which can be placed in
	SYS:WBStartup, if you wish.

@endnode
@node "STARTUP"
@title "Grunch · Startup"


    @{b}Startup@{ub}

	Grunch can be launched from Ambient or from the CLI. If you want Grunch to
	be launched automatically at system start, there is a predefined
	"GrunchWB_Startup" icon which is preconfigured for this job. Drag it over to
	your WBStartup drawer and it will be launched on system start.

@endnode
@node "BASICS"
@title "Grunch · Basics"


    @{b}Basics@{ub}

	How to use Grunch? Well a good start is to install and run it. Using it from
	RAM: is not a good idea as it needs storage for version tracking and other
	config.

	Once you started Grunch it will automagically search images for all
	applications it knows. This may take a while, but it´s worth the waiting and
	it is only a one time scan. Next time you launch Grunch it will only load
	images from new database entries.

	After image loading Grunch is scanning your hard drive for known
	Applications and their location followed by an update check of each
	application found.

	When the scan is finished. You should open preferences and enter the path
	section. Usually on MorphOS there are only Applications, Games and the
	Utilities-drawer, but you may have other folders for internet, audio and
	video applications. Adapt these path gadgets to match your installation. It
	will save much time, as these path will later be used a default for
	installation and update.

	After leaving preferences Grunch will trigger a new scan, as your path changes
	may result in finding more already installed applications.

	If you see an application in list, that is for sure installed, but not marked as
	installed, this can have several reasons. The install path may still be wrong,
	the application drawer or the application binary may be named wrong.

	It is also possible that Grunch claims some applications as outdated, even
	when you are sure they are not. These are mostly applications which are not
	providing proper version information and since Grunch did not install them
	in the first place, it can´t know anything about the version number. Use the
	repair option in such case. Grunch will reinstall latest version and the
	state section will now show the proper state.

	Installing an application is quite easy. Click on the list entry to activate
	it. Use install button or the context menu (right mouse button) over the
	list and select the install item. Grunch starts some checking and opens a
	requester to confirm action. You can disable these requesters in
	preferences.

	The application can be uninstalled in the same way using the uninstall
	button or context menu item.
		
	@{b}Please note@{ub} that you should terminate any application before
	deinstalling it. Drawers and files may be in use. Usually the deinstallation
	will be successful, but you may have some dead files and drawer on drive.

@endnode
@node "SETTINGS"
@title "Grunch · Settings"


    @{b}Settings@{ub}

	Most options in the settings should be self explaining. There is also a
	bubble for each option giving additional information.

	The most important pages are the startup, the miscellaneous and the path
	page.
		
	The startup page is only important if you want to change the startup
	behavior of Grunch. If you have no clue about that, just leave it set to
	defaults.

	On the miscellaneous page you may want to specify a new download directory
	on harddrive to keep all downloaded archives or to disable the keep archives
	option as it makes no sense in RAM:

	Also depending on the memory available it might be a good idea to change the
	temporary drawer to somewhere else, too. A drawer will be created inside
	tempdir, so it is even save to use "SYS:" as temporary storage.

	The path page contains all application related path information. Changing
	these path will not effect your hard drive or any installed application.
	These strings define the path for any type of software you will install in
	the future. So if you setup games path to "Games:" all new games will be
	installed on your games partition by default.

	The other pages are more or less for getting more information or turning off
	requesters. Changing these options will not affect any of the installed
	applications. You can always return to the settings window to revert
	changes.

@endnode
@node "DEVELOPER"
@title "Grunch · Developer"


    @{b}Developer@{ub}

	You are a developer and want to support the Grunch system? No problem. There
	are some simple rules which make your and our lives much easier.

	1) Use a proper version string.

	$VER: NAME VER.REV.BUILD (DD.MM.YY)

	No spaces in NAME, no leading "V" for the version number. No trailing dot
	after revision or build if there is no digit following. No written month
	name. No additional characters to the version codes.

	Correct: $VER: SuperPaint 1.0.0 (24.12.01)
	Wrong:   $VER: Super Paint 1.0.r0. (24-Dec-01)

	2) Name your archives properly.

	If you have to include a version code for some reason, then select a scheme
	and keep that forever. Most common is "NAME-VER.REV.BUILD-SYSTEMOS.lha", so
	"SuperPaint-1.0.0-MorphOS.lha" would be fine.

	3) Provide a readme.

	Providing a standard Aminet-readme is quite a big help. There is no need to
	store version information in the filenames. Just add a "Version: 1.0.0" line
	and name your archive and readme for example "SuperPaint.lha" and
	"SuperPaint.readme"

	4) Drawer inside archive

	Always use a drawer inside your archive and name it after the application
	with a proper case and without version data. So if your application binary
	is named "SuperPaint", the drawer should be named "SuperPaint" as well. By
	doing this and considering no files are needed to be copied elsewhere, your
	installation is just the simplest Grunch.db entry ever and once it is done
	all you need is to clone it and change name and description to make it
	support other applications.

	Basically that´s it. Using a proper makefile for archive creation will save
	much time, when dealing with updates, but as a programmer you should already
	know that. Providing a proper Grunch file for your application is always
	welcome. Just make sure you check the @{"database creation rules" link "DATABASERULES"}, as we try to
	keep the quality high to not end up in a mess.

@endnode

@node "DATABASERULES"
@title "Grunch · Database Rules"


    @{b}Database Rules@{ub}

	The .db files used by Grunch are following a strict rules.
				
	Please read these rules carefully, if you want to contribute your files as
	part of the official Grunch database. It is required to be strict, as I need
	to check all files by hand and I do not want to waste any time repairing and
	cleaning your stuff, because you managed to deliver a messy file.
		
	If your file supports MorphOS only, then "_MorphOS" must be inserted right
	before the .db extension. e.g. "SuperPaint_MorphOS.db" This will limit
	loading to MorphOS.
				
	Use "AmigaOS3" and "AmigaOS4" for other systems. Without any system string,
	the database entry is considered to support all systems.
				
	The case is important! MORPHOS or AMIGAOS4 are not allowed.

    @{b}Case@{ub}

	All Grunch commands are upper case. Its "ITEM" not "item" or "Item".

	Dos commands must be written as they are in MorphOS C: drawer. e.g.
	"Delete", "Copy", "LhA". Keywords are upper case, so they are easy to
	locate.

	Use proper case for any path names. This will avoid troubles for the users
	and make the stuff more clean and readable

    @{b}DOS rules@{ub}

	Installation is running with a fail level of 10. Uninstall with a fail level
	of 30. Only change this, if you know what you are doing.

	Also do not use any QUIET option and do not redirect shell output to NIL:.
	It´s useless as the output is already redirected by Grunch. In addition to
	that you will break the shell output option which allows you to enable a
	shell log while installing and uninstalling. This log becomes very handy,
	once you get problems with your scripts.

    @{b}Alignment@{ub}

	If there are more nearly identical commands in file, align them by inserting
	spaces. See the example files in examples drawer.

	@{b}Pattern@{ub}

	@{"Grunch patterns" link "PATTERN"} are there for a reason. Use them! Even if {TEMPDIR} is most
	likly set to "RAM:". You cannot assume the users wishes and the amount of ram the
	system has available at the moment of installation. Same for all other patterns.

	Use upper case for PATTERNS. {tempdir} is not allowed. One of the most
	important pattern is {NAME} which will be replaced by the ITEM-name.

    @{b}Path@{ub}

	All path names must be set into "" or they may fail. Remember the user can
	have any path and this path may contain spaces, which will break your install
	and deinstall rules.

	All path patterns ({#?DIR} - e.g. {TEMPDIR}) are guaranteed to have a
	trailing slash. Never use "{TEMPDIR}/something". The valid path would be
	"{TEMPDIR}something".

    @{b}The Database-Directory@{ub}

    The Grunch database is located in Grunch/Database directory, which is
    divided into an "internal" and an "user" directory. The "user" directory is
    guaranteed to stay untouched during updates. Place your files only there.
				
	Name your own item files as your item and append a ".db" extension. No
	spaces allowed! Use an system id string to specify the system your entry is
	meant for. "Superpaint.db" is for all systems, while "Superpaint_MorphOS.db"
	is just for MorphOS. If more than one system is supported by an archive,
	support them all.
				
	I know that multiple items in one file are supported, but if you want to
	contribute your files, I make the rules and I expect one single file for
	each item with a proper naming.

    @{b}Undocumented stuff@{ub}

	There are several commands and command arguments for internal usage. You are
	not allowed to use them in any of your files. Even if it works for now, it
	may fail in the future because I don't care about compatibly of undocumented
	features.

    @{b}Test your stuff@{ub}

	Test if your install or deinstall rule is working. Make sure deinstallation
	is deleting the files installed. Do not forget catalogs, help files and
	other stuff as preferences in ENV:. Do it right or I will reject it! Make
	sure you set the proper dependency and the proper application type. Check
	the install section for hints and tips about making own database files.

@endnode
@node "DATABASETIPS"
@title "Grunch · Database Tips"


    @{b}Database Tips@{ub}

	This is a small collection of useful ideas and code snippets, which can be
	used in your own scripts to simplify and enhance them.


    @{b}ITEM-Name@{ub}

	In 99% of all installations it is wise to name an item exactly as the
	directory it gets installed in. This saves loads of work, as you can use
	{NAME} all over the place and Grunch will fill out the stuff itself. More
	important is that you can simply recycle old entries when creating a new
	one. All exampled shown below can be copied into your script without any
	modification if name is properly and the name matches the archive drawer and
	binary. Remember "etw" is bad! "EatTheWhistle" is better!
			

    @{b}Application Icon@{ub}

	The application icon may be adapted by the user. It even may contain custom
	configurations and graphics, so overwriting the file is a quite bad idea. To
	avoid this simply delete the icon in temp directory, when it exists in
	installation directory and before installing the archives contents:

	If EXISTS "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}.info"
	 If EXISTS "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}.info"
	  Delete FORCE "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}.info"
	 EndIf
	Endif

	Installation is running at a fail level of 10. So even trying to delete a
	non existing file will make it break. Use If/EndIf combinations to check
	before deleting files. If you need to delete a bunch of files it may be wise
	to use "FailAt 30" to disarm error handling, but do not forget to reenable
	it by calling "FailAt 10".


    @{b}The Installation@{ub}

	Avoid using MakeDir for creating the target drawer. Copy will do this for
	you. Also note that Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}/#?" is better than Copy
	"{TEMPDIR}{NAME}#?". Of course the second one (without a slash) would work,
	but it has some side effects like loosing the drawer icon in installation
	directory by overwriting. The line below only copies the contents of the
	drawer and creates a new drawer with the name "{NAME}", which includes the
	cases you preset. Also: See directory icon hint below.

	Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}/#?"   "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}" ALL


    @{b}Directory Icon@{ub}

	As the application icon, the drawer icon may be customised by the user and
	it is anoying to fix the icon graphics after each update. This is the
	simplest way to avoid it. Check if the icon is there and if not, copy it
	over.

	If NOT EXISTS "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info"
	 Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}.info"        "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info"
	EndIf

	But there is one side effect. If the lazy developer somehow forgets to
	include the icon when updating the archive, the installation will fail. You
	could cheat around with a FailAt 30, but there is a more elegant way. If the
	icon is also missing in archive, we simply create one using the users system
	presets. Looks complicated, but when ITEM-name is properly set and matching
	the installation, it is just a copy and paste of a few lines.

	If NOT EXISTS "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info"
	 If EXISTS "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}.info"
	  Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}.info" "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info"
	 Else
	  GTooltype "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}" TYPE WBDRAWER
	 EndIf
	EndIf

    @{b}Uninstall@{ub}

	Uninstall is running in FailAt 30 mode, so there is no need to check if a
	file exists before deleting. The uninstall process cannot fail on normal
	commands, unless you use "FailAt 10" to force it, too.

	Uninstalling can be quiet easy. Of course all depends on the quality of the
	installation. If the application was installed into a drawer it can be
	deinstalled with two lines.

	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}" ALL
	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info"

	Yes, I know it is possible to use a pattern ({NAME}#?) to kill the icon
	along with the directory, but that would cause trouble. Just imagine the
	user kept a backup named "{NAME}_old" in the same installation dir.
	Uninstalling with a pattern would erase that data, too. Another example
	would be if applications like "Paint" and "PaintPro" are installed.
	Deinstallation "Paint" with a pattern in deinstall rule would cause
	"PaintPro" to be deinstalled as well. So @{b}NEVER@{ub} use a pattern when
	removing directories.

	If the application is using MUI, then MUI and application settings may be
	stored in ENVARC:MUI and ENV:MUI. When deinstalling the application make
	sure to remove these files, too. Grunch makes it easy to delete these
	preferences, too.

	Delete "ENVARC:MUI/{UPPERNAME}{MUIPREFSPATTERN}" FORCE
	Delete "ENV:MUI/{UPPERNAME}{MUIPREFSPATTERN}"    FORCE

	Upper name is important, as a filesystem may be configured to be case sensitive.
	MUI is always using upper case for appnames. {MUIPREFSPATTERN} is a more or less
	complex DOS pattern, which ensures only the matching files will be removed. Don´t
	think about it! Use it!

@endnode
@node "PATTERN"
@title "Grunch · Pattern"


    @{b}Pattern@{ub}

	To make the Grunch script system as flexible as possible, Grunch provides a
	list of patterns, which will be filled at runtime with data provided by user
	settings and the system itself.

	All patterns are enclosed in braces "{}". If the result is a path, it is
	guarantied to get a trailing '/' or ':'!

	{TEMPDIR}          - Drawer to extract and modify data during installation.
			     Will be wiped afterwards.
	{DOWNLOADDIR}      - Directory the archive was downloaded to. Only valid inside
			     the INSTALL command.
	{INSTALLDIR}       - Directory the user wants to install this app to. Only
			     valid inside the INSTALL and UNINSTALL command.
	{VERSION}          - placeholder for version
	{REVISION}         - placeholder for revision
	{BUILD}            - placeholder for build
	{0REVISION}        - placeholder for revision with leading digits
	{0BUILD}           - placeholder for build with leading digits
	{NAME}             - ITEM-name, useful to alias directory and binary names.
	{UPPERNAME}        - same as {NAME}, but upper case.
	{LOWERNAME}        - same as {NAME}, but lower case.
	{DISPLAYNAME}      - ITEM-display name, useful for requesters.
	{ARCHIVENAME}      - URLARCHIVE string, but with filled pattern
	{EXTENSION}        - URLARCHIVE strings file extension
	{LANGUAGE}         - Current system language e.g. "deutsch", "english", ...
	{SYSOS}
	{SYSCPU}
	{SYSTEMOS}
	{SYSTEMCPU}        - The string will be replaced by a proper case version of
			     the system and cpu name. "SystemOS" results in "MorphOS",
			     While "SYSTEMOS" result in "MORPHOS". Same for AmigaOS4
			     and AmigaOS3. Currently the following versions are
			     supported: "SystemOS", "SYSOS", "systemos", "SYSTEMOS", "sysos",
			     "SYSCPU", "SYSTEMCPU", and  "SystemCPU". These are not only
			     handy when dealing with tagged filename, but also to check the
			     system the installation is done on. See @{"install section" link "CMDINSTALL"} for tips
			     and hints. These are the only pattern where non upper case
			     naming is allowed.
	{DAY}
	{MONTH}
	{YEAR}
	{HOUR}
	{MINUTE}
	{SECOND}           - The patterns will be replaced by their proper date values.
			     All digits will be dumped with a leading zero and the year always has
			     4 digits.
	{MON}              - Month name in English short form. Do not use as target!
	{CHECKNAME}        - If an application for any reason has no valid local version
			     information, then use {CHECKNAME} and perform an
			     Echo  "Version: {VERSION}.{REVISION}.{BUILD}" TO "{CHECKNAME}"
			     to store the version. Use "{CHECKNAME}" as name for the VERSIONCHECK
			     command. Do not forget to delete the file {CHECKNAME} in uninstall
			     part of your script.
	{FPU}              - Set to "ALTIVEC" if AltiVec using is present. If not it will
			     be replaced by nothing. Useful like this If EQ "{FPU}" "ALTIVEC".
	{MUIPREFSPATTERN}  - Pattern for deleting preferences of an application. Use
			     'Delete "ENVARC:MUI/{UPPERNAME}{MUIPREFSPATTERN}"' to delete all
			     preferences files stored on hard drive.

@endnode
@node "SUPERPATTERN"
@title "Grunch · Super Pattern"


    @{b}Super Pattern@{ub}

	Super patterns are like standard patterns, but they represent a highly
	complex shell script.

	All super patterns beside {STANDARDEXTRACT} only work if the {NAME} is
	matching the application name and directory rules.

	All super patterns must be located at the beginning of a line, as they
	result in a multi line script.

	WARNING! It's not allowed to disable this command by using ";". Super
	patterns are multi line patterns and using the ";" would only deactivate the
	first line of the resulting script which causes most likly a failure.

	The big goal of using super patterns is simplicity. Just three lines and
	your Grunch-item backups, extracts and installs your application. In
	addition to that, having the real shell magic in Grunch itself your install
	benefits from future enhancements.

	{STANDARDBACKUP} is the most powerful commands. It takes
	"{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}" and archives the data. Then it checks "ENVARC:" and
	"ENVARC:MUI/" for file matching "{NAME}.prefs" etc and adds them to the
	archive. The destination archive gets renamed with version information and
	stored at the location the user picked to keep backups. Use this command at
	first line in install and uninstall command to create a backup, if your
	application is single drawer based.

	{STANDARDEXTRACT} extracts the archive to "{TEMPDIR}". It uses GGauge to
	inform the user about extracting process and takes care about using the
	proper shell command (Lha, UnZip, XADUnFile ) to perform the action on the
	running OS.

	{STANDARDCOPY} in easy words copies the source drawer to the install
	directory and takes care about the drawer and application icon. It checks if
	"{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}.info" exists and delete from "{TEMPDIR}" location
	to prevent the user icon being overwritten. Then the entire drawer get
	copied from "{TEMPDIR}" to "{INSTALLDIR}". Afterwards Grunch will copy or
	create the application drawer icon, if it does not exists in "{INSTALLDIR}".

	{CREATEWBSTARTUPICON} simply clones the "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}.info" to
	"{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}_WBStartup.info" if the destination is missing.
	Once done, it adapts the type to WBProject and sets the application path to
	the install location. This allows the user to simply drag and drop this icon
	to his WBStartup-directory for autostart.

@endnode
@node "COMMANDS"
@title "Grunch · Commands"


    @{b}Commands@{ub}

	Please read the chapter about the @{"Grunch patterns" link "PATTERN"} first, as this may gives
	you a bettern understanding how flexible a simple Grunch database entry can
	be.

	The following commands are allowed to be used:

	@{" APPAUTHOR     " link "CMDAPPAUTHOR"     }
	@{" APPPICTURE    " link "CMDAPPPICTURE"    }
	@{" APPTYPE       " link "CMDAPPTYPE"       }
	@{" APPWEBPAGE    " link "CMDAPPWEBPAGE"    }
	@{" APPDIRECTORY  " link "CMDAPPDIRECTORY"  }
	@{" ARCHIVESIZE   " link "CMDARCHIVESIZE"   }
	@{" DATE          " link "CMDDATE"          }
	@{" DEPENDENCIES  " link "CMDDEPENDENCIES"  }
	@{" DESCRIPTION   " link "CMDDESCRIPTION"   }
	@{" GRUNCHAUTHOR  " link "CMDGRUNCHAUTHOR"  }
	@{" INSTALL       " link "CMDINSTALL"       }
	@{" INSTALLCHECK  " link "CMDINSTALLCHECK"  }
	@{" INSTALLDIR    " link "CMDINSTALLDIR"    }
	@{" ITEM          " link "CMDITEM"          }
	@{" UNINSTALL     " link "CMDUNINSTALL"     }
	@{" URLARCHIVE    " link "CMDURLARCHIVE"    }
	@{" URLPATTERN    " link "CMDURLPATTERN"    }
	@{" URLREADME     " link "CMDURLREADME"     }
	@{" URLWEBPAGE    " link "CMDURLWEBPAGE"    }
	@{" VERSIONCHECK  " link "CMDVERSIONCHECK"  }

@endnode
@node "CMDITEM"
@title "Grunch · Commands - ITEM"


    @{b}ITEM@{ub}

	ITEM is the main command inside a database. It defines a new grunch item by
	its name. This name is important and should be chosen properly. Each ITEM
	command must be followed by a matching ITEM END command, that terminates the
	item creation process. Without a proper ITEM END the entire ITEM will be
	rejected. You should also know that the name argument can be aliased by the
	{NAME} pattern in following script. This saves a lot of time when archives
	are made properly and directories, binaries and archives follow the same
	naming rule. Spaces are not allowed.

	If the Programm ist named "GreatGame", then the drawer and the binary should
	be named "GreatGame", too. If this is not the case, because you did not
	create the archive or the makefile creating an archive, then rename the
	drawers and games before calling standard install. This is easy and the
	result looks nice. Who knows that the drawer "etw" contains? "EatTheWhistle"
	is the better choice here.

	DISPLAYNAME allows to show a different name than the data base entry name.
	If there is a e.g. a plugin for some application, use "Applicationname -" as
	prefix for the name. This allows the user to sort all plugins for software
	by performing a simple name sort.

	UNINSTALLWARN is kind of special. Some applications (e.g. mail applications)
	collect a huge amount of important data. In most cases this data is stored
	within the application directory, so a simple uninstall could cause a
	massive loss of important data. This switch triggers an additional warning
	request, which cannot be disabled by settings.

	TEMPLATE:

	ITEM/A,DISPLAYNAME/K,UNINSTALLWARN/S

	EXAMPLE:

	## ITEM "SuperPaint"
	## ITEM END

	## ITEM "SuperPaint" "DISPLAYNAME "Super Paint"
	## ITEM END

	## ITEM "redeye.plugin" "DISPLAYNAME "Super Paint - Red Eye Reduction plugin"
	## ITEM END

	## ITEM "SuperMail" UNINSTALLWARN
	## ITEM END

@endnode
@node "CMDDATE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - DATE"


    @{b}DATE@{ub}

	DATE specifies the date when you wrote the database file. This is used to
	sort Grunch list by age. The format is day number with a leading 0 followed
	by a dot and the month number with leading 0. The month is followed by a dot
	and finally the year with 4 digits is specified. No time and no other
	information are allowed.


	TEMPLATE:

	DATE/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## DATE "09.01.2011"

@endnode
@node "CMDDESCRIPTION"
@title "Grunch · Commands - DESCRIPTION"


    @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}

	DESCRIPTION gives a description on the application defined. This command can
	be enlarged to a multi line text by simply specifying no text behind the
	command. Like it is done for the INSTALL and UNINSTALL command a
	"DESCRIPTION END" line is required. The first line should be a short
	overview as it may be shown in the Grunch list.

	TEMPLATE:

	DESCRIPTION/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## DESCRIPTION "Uber cool paint program"

	## DESCRIPTION
	Uber cool paint program
	Second line
	Third line
	## DESCRIPTION END

@endnode
@node "CMDAPPTYPE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - APPTYPE"


    @{b}APPTYPE@{ub}

	This setting is very important. It defines not only the type used for list
	sorting in the Grunch Application. It also predefines the path used for
	installation. Currently the following types are available: AUDIO, VIDEO,
	TEXT, PICTURE, GAME, NETWORK, TOOL, UTILITY, DRIVER, APPLICATION,
	DESKTOP, SKIN, CLASS, LIBRARY, SCREENBAR, DEVELOPER and GRUNCH.

	While the most types are all present in path section of the Grunch
	preferences, the last five are not. The reason is simple. Their path is pre
	or undefined.
			
	"DRIVER", "CLASS", "LIBRARY" and "SCREENBAR" have no path at all, as these
	components usually have fixed locations to be stored. "SKIN" is relative to
	some application using the INSTALLDIR DEPENDENCY option or has a fixed
	location in system.

	Finally the GRUNCH type. It is reserved for maintaining Grunch and its
	database files. It is considered as driver like, so no special path. If you
	create a Grunch database to share with friends, then use the GRUNCH type.


	TEMPLATE:

	APPTYPE/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## APPTYPE "TOOL"

@endnode
@node "CMDAPPWEBPAGE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - APPWEBPAGE"


    @{b}APPWEBPAGE@{ub}

	This is simply the web page of the software this Grunch entry is about. If
	the website contains sub pages for several projects, then link to this
	specific application, so the user can find the product information he needs.
			
	Even if it is completely optional and has nothing to do with version
	detection, it should be specified. If there is no real page, then point to
	the download page.


	TEMPLATE:

	APPWEBPAGE/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## APPWEBPAGE "http://www.superpaint.org"

@endnode
@node "CMDAPPAUTHOR"
@title "Grunch · Commands - APPAUTHOR"


    @{b}APPAUTHOR@{ub}

	This is simply the author of the software this Grunch entry is about.
	Specify the name followed by the E-Mail address if possible.

	The use of the E-Mail address is that the user will be able to send bug
	reports using Grunch.

	NOTE: Since the Grunch database is a simple text file, it may be parsed by
	robots collecting email addresses. To avoid this use "&" instead of an "\@"
	and "$" instead of a dot. The address must be specified in <> to be detected
	by Grunch.

	TEMPLATE:

	APPAUTHOR/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## APPAUTHOR "Heinz Superpaint <heinzsuperpaint&superpaint$org>"

@endnode
@node "CMDAPPPICTURE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - APPPICTURE"


    @{b}APPPICTURE@{ub}

	This is a link to an image stored in the web showing the application. Please
	avoid any huge screenshots, as the result will be a small image without any
	use, when displayed. Screenshots only work for games. Use application logos
	if possible. Better use no image than a bad one, as Grunch will use a type
	base image to fill the gap.
			

	TEMPLATE:

	APPPICTURE/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## APPPICTURE "http://www.superpaint.org/images/supershot.jpg"

@endnode
@node "CMDAPPDIRECTORY"
@title "Grunch · Commands - APPDIRECTORY"

	
    @{b}APPDIRECTORY@{ub}

	APPDIRECTORY is used to determine the directory to open with the context
	menu, when INSTALLDIR is disabled and not linked to another application
	using an INSTALLDEPENDENCY.

	This is usualy required for system updates or driver installations
	containing tools or utilities and not needed for custom applications.
						

	TEMPLATE:

	APPDIRECTORY/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## APPDIRECTORY "SYS:Utilities/Commodities/"

@endnode
@node "CMDARCHIVESIZE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - ARCHIVESIZE"


    @{b}ARCHIVESIZE@{ub}

	The archive size is used to inform the user about the size of an application
	to install. This is handy for people with slow or expensive internet access.
	The size information can made visible using the list title context menu.

	The specified value is in bytes. It does not matter if it is exact, but it
	should be near the actual archive size. Normally application archives do
	not grow by mega bytes and it does not matter if an archive is 1200000 or
	1200010 bytes in size. So just add the archive size valid when making the
	database entry and it will be fine.
		
	A proper value gives the user an idea how much data will be downloaded for
	installation, so he can calculate costs and time needed.


	TEMPLATE:

	ARCHIVESIZE/A/N

	EXAMPLES:

	## ARCHIVESIZE 123456
	## ARCHIVESIZE 78567

@endnode
@node "CMDDEPENDENCIES"
@title "Grunch · Commands - DEPENDENCIES"


    @{b}DEPENDENCIES@{ub}

	This setting is very important. If the application needs specific mui
	classes, a library or another application, then the ITEM-name should be
	specified here.

	When installing the user gets notified about missing components and can
	choose to install them or abort installation of the item needing the
	external installation. During deinstallation the user gets warned if the
	item he is about to deinstall will break other packets.

	TEMPLATE:

	DEPENDENCIES/A/M

	EXAMPLE:

	## DEPENDENCIES "Super.library" "EvenMoreSuper.library"

	It is also possible to limit dependencies to a specific OS.

	## DEPENDENCIES "Super.library" MORPHOS "EvenMoreSuper.library"

    On all systems the "Super.library" is required. MorphOS also requires the
    "EvenMoreSuper.library" to be installed for proper operation. Once a system
    id is used, all following dependencies are limited to that specific system
    unless a new system id is used. Using "ANY" as system id will switch back to
    the all system mode. "ANY" is also used as default, when no system id is
    specified.

@endnode
@node "CMDGRUNCHAUTHOR"
@title "Grunch · Commands - GRUNCHAUTHOR"


    @{b}GRUNCHAUTHOR@{ub}

	This is simply the name of the guy who created the database entry for
	Grunch. Usually it should be the name followed by an E-Mail address enclosed
	with <>.

	NOTE: Since the Grunch database is a simple text file, it may be parsed by
	robots collecting email addresses. To avoid this use "&" instead of an "\@"
	and "$" instead of a dot. The address must be specified in <> to be detected
	by Grunch.


	TEMPLATE:

	GRUNCHAUTHOR/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## GRUNCHAUTHOR "Guido Mersmann <geit&gmx$de>"

@endnode
@node "CMDURLARCHIVE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - URLARCHIVE"


    @{b}URLARCHIVE@{ub}

	URLARCHIVE defines the archive location on a server. Specify the complete
	URL here. Depending on the page and name you may need to include {VERSION}
	or {REVISION} as pattern for the version code. Grunch will use this also as
	a pattern, if the PATTERN Command is not specified.

	TEMPLATE:

	URLARCHIVE/A

	EXAMPLES:

	## URLARCHIVE "http://www.soft.de/dlds/SuperPaint.lha"
	## URLARCHIVE "http://www.soft.de/dlds/SuperPaint_{VERSION}.{REVISION}.lha"

@endnode
@node "CMDURLREADME"
@title "Grunch · Commands - URLREADME"


    @{b}URLREADME@{ub}

	URLREADME defines a text file location on a server. Specify the complete URL
	here. The readme-file is used to obtain the version information of the
	server side located application archive. A standard Aminet-readme file,
	which contains "Version:" string followed by a version code, is expected.
			
	However Grunch also performs a standard version string check on that file as
	a fallback, so version information stored in "$VER: name v.r.b (dd.mm.yy)"
	format are handled as well.

	TEMPLATE:

	URLREADME/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## URLREADME "http://www.soft.de/dlds/SuperPaint.readme"

@endnode
@node "CMDURLWEBPAGE"
@title "Grunch · Commands - URLWEBPAGE"


    @{b}URLWEBPAGE@{ub}

	URLWEBPAGE is NOT the home page of the software to install. It may be the
	same page, but it may also be some download page. URLWEBPAGE is the page where
	the version information of the software is located. If no readme file is
	available the only way to obtain version information is to scan the webpage
	itself.

	By default the file part of the URLARCHIVE command is used as pattern to
	scan the page for the most recent version of the application. This only
	works if the URLARCHIVE command contains at least {VERSION} as placeholder
	for the pattern scan. It does not matter if there are hundreds of different
	versions listed on that specific page. The pattern scan will detect them all
	and pick the highest version code for version compare and archive download.
	If the scan pattern needs to be different than the URLARCHIVE name, use the
	URLPATTERN argument to adapt.

	TEMPLATE:

	URLWEBPAGE/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## URLWEBPAGE "http://www.soft.de/superpaint/downloads.html"

@endnode
@node "CMDURLPATTERN"
@title "Grunch · Commands - URLPATTERN"


    @{b}URLPATTERN@{ub}

	URLPATTERN is a scan pattern for web page scanning. It is required that the
	pattern contains at least {VERSION} or no scan takes place. The pattern must
	not contain any URL path. Just the pattern is allowed here. It is not even
	required to contain a file name. Remember it is a pattern which gets
	compared with the entire page.

	TEMPLATE:

	URLPATTERN/A

	EXAMPLES:

	## URLPATTERN "superpaint_{VERSION}.{REVISION}.lha"
	## URLPATTERN "latest SuperPaint is V{VERSION}.{REVISION}"

@endnode
@node "CMDINSTALLDIR"
@title "Grunch · Commands - INSTALLDIR"


    @{b}INSTALLDIR@{ub}

	A path specified by INSTALLDIR overrides the prefs install path by using the
	predefined one. Avoid this path at any cost. It's not helpful, when the
	users preselected path, for let's say "games" becomes invalid, because you
	deceided to install your game to "SYS:Applications". Set a proper
	APPTYPE and skip this command.

	On the other hand there may be software, that needs no specific path. When
	it is a DRIVER simply use the APPTYPE driver. When the driver does not
	contain any custom path for driver specific software, at well as when parts
	of the OS get replaced, use "DISABLED" switch and even the user is unable to
	change the path.

	Please note, that if the install directory gets DISABLED, the pattern
	{INSTALLDIR} is undefined and must not be used.

	The DEPENDENCY argument is useful for applications that have plugins inside
	their home directories. E.g. if your SuperPaint application supports plugins
	and there is a third party plugin for red eye reduction, then simply create
	a grunch database entry for that plugin and define a dependency like shown
	in the examples below. In the result the user cannot choose the path as the
	plugin always gets installed where the paints application is located.


	TEMPLATE:

	INSTALLDIR,DISABLED/S,DEPENDENCY/K

	EXAMPLES:

	## INSTALLDIR "SYS:Musik/"
	## INSTALLDIR DISABLED
	## INSTALLDIR DEPENDENCY "SuperPaint"

@endnode
@node "CMDINSTALLCHECK"
@title "Grunch · Commands - INSTALLCHECK"


    @{b}INSTALLCHECK@{ub}

	INSTALLCHECK points onto a file or directory on hard disk, that is only
	present if the installation was done. This can also be the file used to
	obtain the version code from. In that case you can spare the VERSIONCHECK
	command. Avoid using a directory if possible.

	It is required to use the Grunch Patterns for getting proper path
	information. NEVER hardcode any path, if the user is able to change the
	path, this would break users choice to install the programs wherever he
	wants. Use {INSTALLDIR} as path to the location where the application was
	installed.
			
	NOTES:

	{INSTALLDIR} is NOT the application directory. It's the directory where the
	application or it's drawer was installed to.

	{INSTALLDIR} is guaranteed to end with a trailing "/" or ":", so a correct
	path is "{INSTALLDIR}ApplicationDir" and not "{INSTALLDIR}/ApplicationDir"

	TEMPLATE:

	INSTALLCHECK/A

	EXAMPLES:

	## INSTALLCHECK "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint/SuperPaint"
	## INSTALLCHECK "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}"

	It is also possible to specify multiple path information and to limit them
	to a specific OS.

	## INSTALLCHECK "SYS:File" "SYS:C/File" MorphOS "SYS:MorphOS/File"

	"SYS:" and "SYS:C" will be checked on all systems. When running on MorphOS
	the third path will be used, if the first checks did not give any positive
	result. Once a system id is used, all following paths are limited to that
	specific system unless a new system id is used. Using "ANY" as type will
	switch back to the all system mode. "ANY" is also used as default, when no
	system id is specified.

@endnode
@node "CMDVERSIONCHECK"
@title "Grunch · Commands - VERSIONCHECK"


    @{b}VERSIONCHECK@{ub}

	VERSIONCHECK points onto a file on hard disk, that contains the version
	code. If this command is not present Grunch tries to obtain the version
	using the file specified with the INSTALLCHECK command.

	It is required to use the Grunch Patterns for getting proper path
	information. NEVER hardcode any path, this would break users choice to
	install the programs wherever he wants. Use {INSTALLDIR} as path to the
	location where the application was installed.
			
	NOTES:

	{INSTALLDIR} is NOT the application directory. It's the directory where the
	application or it's drawer was installed to.

	{INSTALLDIR} is guaranteed to end with a trailing "/" or ":", so a correct
	path is "{INSTALLDIR}ApplicationDir" and not "{INSTALLDIR}/ApplicationDir"

	TEMPLATE:

	VERSIONCHECK/A

	EXAMPLES:

	## VERSIONCHECK "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint/SuperPaint"
	## VERSIONCHECK "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}/{NAME}"

	It is also possible to specify multiple path information and to limit them
	to a specific OS.

	## INSTALLCHECK "SYS:File" "SYS:C/File" MorphOS "SYS:MorphOS/File"

	"SYS:" and "SYS:C" will be checked on all systems. When running on MorphOS
	the third path will be used, if the first checks did not give any positive
	result. Once a system id is used, all following paths are limited to that
	specific system unless a new system id is used. Using "ANY" as type will
	switch back to the all system mode. "ANY" is also used as default, when no
	system id is specified.

@endnode
@node "CMDINSTALL"
@title "Grunch · Commands - INSTALL"


    @{b}INSTALL@{ub}

	INSTALL contains the entire install script for the application and needs to
	be terminated with INSTALL END.

	It is required to use the @{"Grunch patterns" link "PATTERN"} for getting
	proper path information. NEVER hardcode any path, this would break users
	choice to install the programs wherever he wants. Use {INSTALLDIR} as path
	to the location where the application will be installed. {TEMPDIR} for
	extracting and dealing with temporary files. Never ever use "RAM:" or "T:"
	for temp storage, as memory may be limited. {DOWNLOADDIR} contains the file
	you just downloaded. {VERSION}, {REVISION} and {BUILD} the version number of
	the application. {NAME} is a very handy pattern. It allows to reuse the item
	name as directory and file name without typing it over and over. Check the
	@{"Grunch pattern" link "PATTERN"} section for detailed information on the
	available patterns.

	The install script is using a fail level of 10 by default. This is very
	important! If you need to create any drawer using MakeDir, then it will fail
	if the directory already exists. This in the most cases is unwanted, so set
	FailAt to 30, create all your directories and reset FailAt to 10 again, like
	it is done in second example.

	TEMPLATE:

	INSTALL/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## INSTALL
	LhA x "{DOWNLOADDIR}SuperPaint_{VERSION}.{REVISION}.{SUBREVISION}.lha" "{TEMPDIR}"
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}SuperPaint/#?"   "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint"      FORCE ALL
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}SuperPaint.info" "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint.info" FORCE
	## INSTALL END

	## INSTALL
	FailAt 30
	MakeDir "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint Pro"
	FailAt 10
	If "{SYSTEMID}" EQ "MORPHOS"
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}SuperPaint_{SystemID}" TO "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint Pro/SuperPaint"
	Else
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}SuperPaint_AmigaOS3"   TO "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint Pro/SuperPaint"
	Endif
	## INSTALL END

	## INSTALL
	LhA x "{DOWNLOADDIR}{NAME}_{VERSION}.{REVISION}.{SUBREVISION}.lha" "{TEMPDIR}"
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}/#?"   "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}"      FORCE ALL
	Copy "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}.info" "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}.info" FORCE
	## INSTALL END

	If you want to launch an existing installer script for some reason, you can
	do it like it is done in the following example:

	## INSTALL
	{STANDARDEXTRACT}
	Cd "{TEMPDIR}{NAME}"
	Installer SCRIPT Install APPNAME "{NAME}" MINUSER 0 DEFUSER 0 NOLOG
	## INSTALL END


@endnode
@node "CMDUNINSTALL"
@title "Grunch · Commands - UNINSTALL"


    @{b}UNINSTALL@{ub}

	UNINSTALL contains the entire uninstall script for the application and needs
	to be terminated with UNINSTALL END.

	Make sure you delete all files you installed and be carefully with DOS
	pattern. Never try to "Delete FORCE ALL {INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint#?" just to
	get rid of the icon. Make two lines:

	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint" ALL
	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint.info"
		
	This avoids deleting any other data the user may want to keep. Would be bad
	if the install script wipes "SuperPaint" and "SuperPaintPro" just because
	you were to lazy.

	The uninstall script is using a fail level of 30 by default, so no need to
	check if a drawer or file exists before calling the delete command.

	For more information check @{"INSTALL" link "CMDINSTALL"} and @{"Grunch pattern" link "PATTERN"} section.

	TEMPLATE:

	UNINSTALL/A

	EXAMPLE:

	## UNINSTALL
	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint" ALL
	Delete FORCE "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint.info"
	## UNINSTALL END

@endnode
@node "SHELLCOMMANDS"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands"


    @{b}Shell Commands@{ub}

	The installation process often requires some more work than just copying
	files. That's why Grunch provides some specialised shell commands to make
	installation easier and possible without depending on external tools which
	may not exist on the system Grunch is running on.

	The following shell commands are currently included:

	@{" GDownload     " link "CMDGDOWNLOAD"     }  download a file
	@{" GGauge        " link "CMDGGauge"        }  controls the progress bar
	@{" GSignal       " link "CMDGSIGNAL"       }  signal one or more tasks
	@{" GStartup      " link "CMDGSTARTUP"      }  user-startup editing tool
	@{" GTooltype     " link "CMDGTOOLTYPE"     }  Tooltype and icon tool

@endnode
@node "CMDGDOWNLOAD"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands - GDownload"


    @{b}GDownload@{ub}

	GDownload allows to download a file from installation rule. This may be
	useful, when a multi archive application needs to be installed.

	Note: You must not use WGet or any other tool for downloading. GDownload is
	specially designed for Grunch and will get important updates in the future
	to e.g. show the download progress in Grunch window.

	TEMPLATE:

	URL/A,NAME=TO/K

	DESCRIPTION:

	URL is the source to download the file from.

	NAME specified the name to save the file to.

	EXAMPLES:

	GDownload "http://www.superpaint.org/icons/icon.png" TO "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint.info"
	GDownload "http://www.superpaint.org/SuperPaint"     NAME "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint"

@endnode
@node "CMDGGAUGE"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands - GGauge"


    @{b}GGauge@{ub}

	GGauge is kind of special. It allows the install script to control the
	progress gauge within the Grunch main window. This is e.g. useful, when
	dealing with long term operations.

	Note: The command is only working during install rule.

	TEMPLATE:

	TYPE/A,NAME/A,CURRENT/N,MAX/N

	DESCRIPTION:

	TYPE is a key word used to specify the displayed text. Valid definitions are
	"PROCESSING", "EXTRACTING", "INSTALLING", "UNINSTALLING", "BACKUP" and
	"WAITINGFORUSER".

	NAME depending on the TYPE this is "{NAME}" or just the archive name your are
	dealing with.

	CURRENT is the value which defines gauge current position. This value is
	also used in text.

	MAX is the maximum gauge position.

	EXAMPLES:

	GGauge "EXTRACTING" "pack1.lha" 1 3
	GGauge "INSTALLING" "{NAME}"

@endnode
@node "CMDGSIGNAL"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands - GSignal"


    @{b}GSignal@{ub}

	GSignal allows to signal a specific task. This may be useful to terminate
	already installed applications before uninstalling them.

	TEMPLATE:

	"NAME/A,SIGNALMASK/K,SIGNAL=SIGNALS/K/N/M"

	DESCRIPTION:

	NAME specified the name of the task. The name may contain pattern for
	multiple task signalling.
		
	SIGNALMASK is maximum of 8 digits hex value with all bits set to trigger.

	SIGNALS is a list of decimal signals to set.

	The most useful signal and the only signals which are static. Unless and
	application has some predefine internally these signals are 12, 13, 14 and
	15, which correspond with CTRL-C, CTRL-D, CTRL-E and CTRL-F shell break
	sequences.

	EXAMPLES:

	GSignal "#?superpaint#?" SIGNALS 14 15
	GSignal "#?superpaint#?" SIGNAL  12
	GSignal "#?superpaint#?" SIGNALMASK f00

@endnode
@node "CMDGSTARTUP"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands - GStartup"


    @{b}GStartup@{ub}

	GStartup allows to insert and remove entries to the user-startup in a quite
	unique way. The application commands get enclosed in ";BEGIN" and ";END"
	lines. The same technique is used by the Installer application.

	TEMPLATE:

	"APPNAME/K/A,LINES/K/M"

	DESCRIPTION:

	APPNAME is a proper application name. Once again if the Grunch ITEM-name and
	the application were designed properly you simply can use APPNAME "{NAME}"
	as argument here.
		
	LINES allows to add lines to the user-startup. To remove all lines of this
	application simply do not specify the LINES argument.

	EXAMPLES:

	GStartup "SuperPaint" LINES "Assign SuperPaint: "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint"
	GStartup "{NAME}"     LINES "Assign {NAME}: "{INSTALLDIR}{NAME}"
	GStartup "{NAME}"

@endnode
@node "CMDGTOOLTYPE"
@title "Grunch · Shell Commands - GTooltype"


    @{b}GTooltype@{ub}

	GTooltype allows to change all icon information needed to allow a proper
	installation from shell.


	TEMPLATE:

	"NAME/A,TYPE/K,X/K/N,Y/K/N,DEFAULTTOOL/K,STACK/K/N,TOOLTYPES/K/M"

	DESCRIPTION:

	NAME is the icon name @{b}without@{ub} the ".info" extension.
			
	TYPE defines the icon type. WBDRAWER, WBTOOL and WBPROJECT are the most
	common.
			
	X,Y are numeric coordination values for fixed icon positioning. -1 is auto
	positioning. Not specifying any coordinate will leave it untouched.

	DEFAULTTOOL is the program to start when clicking on this icon and the icon
	type is project.

	STACK is a numeric value to define the applications stack. Only values
	bigger than 4096 are allowed.

	TOOLTYPES allows modifications to the defined config lines inside an icon.
	Each tooltype needs two different strings. First is the name, the second the
	contents. A contents of "" means it is just a switch. A contents of "-" will
	remove the first tooltype with this name from tooltype list. There is no
	limit on the number of tooltypes specified.

	EXAMPLES:

	GTooltype "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint" TYPE WBDRAWER
	GTooltype "{INSTALLDIR}SuperPaint/SuperPaint" TOOLTYPES "RTG" "-" "RTG" "YES"

@endnode

@node "FAQ"
@title "Grunch · FAQ"


	@{b}Frequently Asked Questions@{ub}

    o I just installed Grunch, but some applications are shown as installed but
      outdated, but they aren´t outdated. Why?

	Well, some (or better many) applications, libraries, devices and other tools
	simply don´t provide a valid version string, so Grunch is not able to detect
	the currently installed version. To keep track Grunch needs to store such
	information on its own. Simply select the repair option to repair your
	installation and create such version data file. Feel free to contact the
	developers for fixing their version strings.

    o Grunch does not find many of my installed applications and claims these are
      not installed. Why?

	The reason is simple. It's not possible to detect an application by a random
	name. This is done to keep installation save, without data loss and to push
	the user a little to keep his drives clean. On the other side, what did you
	expect should Grunch do, if it finds the drawers "OWB-Old", "OWB-1.13" and
	"OWB-UpToDate"? Just rename the main drawer to the real application name and
	restart Grunch. Now it will find the application. Same for the programm name
	itself.

    o I have a cool application which is missing in the database. Can you add it?

	Well, sure I can. All I need is a proper source for the file and some
	information. Proper in this case means stable. Building a database entry on
	top of a news post makes no sense, as the new post will vanish and same may
	happen to the file. Sources like MorphOS-Files, Aminet or a developer pages
	are preferred.

    o Is it possible to create a database file for any Application available on
      the internet?

	Basically yes. It is even possible to track catalogs or text files. All it
	requires is a proper version or date information that can be obtained from
	the source. There are several brain dead file names and version variations,
	which cannot be handled properly. I simply cannot support broken versions
	like 0.0.3b1 or other bull shit. Blame the developers in such case.

    o What happens if I decide to no longer use Grunch?

	Grunch is just a tool for installation and deinstallation. If you delete it,
	all applications installed with it, will stay intact and will work. You are
	just on your own to find and install updates.

@endnode
